Aim
To write a C++ program that demonstrates function overloading applied to the member functions of a class.

Algorithm
Start the program.
Create a class with at least two or more functions having the same name but different parameter lists.
Inside the class, define the overloaded functions.
Create an object of the class.
Call the overloaded functions using the object by passing different numbers or types of arguments.
Observe how the correct function is invoked based on the argument list.
Display the result.
End the program.

Program (C++)
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Calculator {
public:
    // Function with one parameter
    void add(int a) {
        cout << "Addition with one parameter: " << a << endl;
    }

    // Overloaded function with two parameters
    void add(int a, int b) {
        cout << "Addition with two parameters: " << a + b << endl;
    }

    // Overloaded function with three parameters
    void add(int a, int b, int c) {
        cout << "Addition with three parameters: " << a + b + c << endl;
    }
};

int main() {
    Calculator obj;

    obj.add(10);          // Calls 1st function
    obj.add(10, 20);      // Calls 2nd function
    obj.add(10, 20, 30);  // Calls 3rd function

    return 0;
}

Output (Result)
Addition with one parameter: 10
Addition with two parameters: 30
Addition with three parameters: 60

Result
Thus, the program successfully demonstrates function overloading applied to the member functions of a class in C++.
